Braskem, E-CL, Gruma, Grupo Mexico, Redecard: Latin America Equity Preview

-- B y   B r y a n   G i b e l   a n d   J o n a t h a n   J .   L e v i n
-- 
2011-07-28T05:02:08Z

-- http://www.bloomberg.com/news/2011-07-28/braskem-e-cl-gruma-grupo-mexico-redecard-latin-america-equity-preview.html
The following companies may have
unusual price changes in Latin American trading. Stock symbols
are in parentheses and share prices reflect the previous close.  The MSCI  Latin America  Index fell 2.6 percent to 4,262.75.  Brazil   Braskem SA (BRKM5)  (BRKM5 BS): Standard & Poor’s Ratings Services
said yesterday that its ratings on Latin America’s largest
petrochemicals producer aren’t affected by the announced
acquisition of polypropylene plants in the U.S. and  Germany  from
Dow Chemical Co. Braskem’s shares climbed 1 percent to 19.40
reais.  Cia. Siderurgica Nacional SA (CSNA3 BS): Brazil’s third-
largest steelmaker said it boosted its stake in  Usinas
Siderurgicas de Minas Gerais SA (USIM5)  (USIM5 BS) to 10.84 percent of
the steelmaker’s common shares and 10.20 percent of preferred
shares, according to a regulatory filing yesterday. CSN shares
retreated 0.3 percent to 16.25 reais. Usiminas declined 0.2
percent to 11.03 reais.  Redecard SA (RDCD3)  (RDCD3 BS): Brazil’s second-largest card-
payment processor by market value said profit fell 14 percent in
the second quarter to 322.6 million reais ($207 million). The
result beat the average estimate of 291.8 million reais from
nine analysts surveyed by Bloomberg. The stock slipped 0.4
percent to 25 reais.  Chile   E-CL SA (ECL CC): The unit of  France ’s GDF Suez agreed to
discuss the purchase of wind farm operator Eolico Monte Redondo
SA from Suez for an undisclosed amount, according to a statement
posted on the website of Chile’s securities regulator. The stock
sank 2.3 percent to 1,233.50 pesos.  Embotelladora Andina SA (AKO/A)  : Chile’s largest Coca-
Cola bottler had second-quarter net income of 14.8 billion pesos
($32 million), down from 15.9 billion pesos a year earlier,
according to data posted on the website of the country’s
securities regulator. The shares slid 1.1 percent to 2,072.10
pesos.  Colombia   Bancolombia SA (BCOLO)  : The nation’s biggest bank sold
800 billion pesos ($453 million) worth of bonds in the Colombian
market yesterday, according to the stock exchange. The shares
dropped 2 percent to 28,320 pesos.  Grupo de Inversiones Suramericana SA (GRUPOSUR)  : The
parent company of Colombia’s largest bank said it is seeking to
offer shares worth about $1.4 billion in Colombia and $700
million overseas by October. The stock declined 2.2 percent to
35,400 pesos.  Mexico  Axtel SAB (AXTELCPO MM): Mexico’s second-largest land-line
phone company reported second-quarter earnings before interest,
taxes, depreciation and amortization of 935 million pesos ($80
million). Sales fell to 2.7 billion pesos, San Pedro Garza
Garcia, Mexico-based Axtel said yesterday in a statement
distributed by  Business Wire . The shares rose 1 percent to 6.77
pesos.  Consorcio Ara SAB (ARA* MM):  Mexico ’s fourth-largest
homebuilder reported second-quarter net income of 221 million
pesos and sales of 1.9 billion pesos, according to a filing with
the Mexican stock exchange. The stock advanced 2.2 percent to
5.99 pesos.  Gruma SAB (GRUMAB MM): Mexico’s largest maker of corn flour
for tortillas reported second-quarter net income of 106 million
pesos and sales of 13.1 billion pesos, the company said in a
filing to the Mexican stock exchange. The shares added 0.1
percent to 24.36 pesos.  Grupo Carso SAB (GCARSOA1 MM): The holding company
controlled by billionaire  Carlos Slim  reported second-quarter
net income of 962 million pesos and sales of 17.5 billion pesos.
The stock decreased 0.7 percent to 33.3 pesos.  Grupo Mexico SAB (GMEXICOB MM): The country’s largest
mining company had its debt outlook raised to positive from
stable by  Standard & Poor’s , which cited resumed operations at
the Buenavista mine, according to an e-mailed statement. The
shares rose 0.8 percent to 42.72 pesos.  Peru   Cia. de Minas Buenaventura SA (BVN PE): Peru’s biggest
precious-metals producer said its board of directors approved
the development of the Minas Conga gold and copper deposit in
Peru. The $4.8 billion project, a joint venture with Newmont
Mining Corp., is slated to start production by the end of 2014,
Lima-based Buenaventura said in an e-mailed statement. The
shares fell 3.4 percent to $41.22.  To contact the reporters on this story:
